Customer Campaign Groups — Generate All Possible Subsets"

In a customer data analysis system, you are given a list of unique customer IDs. You need to generate all possible subsets of these customer IDs. Each subset represents a possible group of customers that can be targeted in a marketing campaign.

You are tasked with implementing a function that returns all possible subsets of a given list of unique customer IDs. Each subset should be represented as a list of customer IDs.

Input format :
A list of unique integers nums[] representing customer IDs.





Output format :
A list of lists where each list represents a subset of customer IDs.



Code constraints :
The number of customer IDs (nums.length) will be between 0 and 10.

Each customer ID will be a unique integer.

Sample test cases :
Input 1 :
3
1 2 3
Output 1 :
All possible subsets:
[]
[1]
[1, 2]
[1, 2, 3]
[1, 3]
[2]
[2, 3]
[3]
Input 2 :
2
4 5
Output 2 :
All possible subsets:
[]
[4]
[4, 5]
[5]


#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

void solve(int idx, vector<int>& nums,
           vector<int>& temp,
           vector<vector<int>>& ans) {

    // store current subset
    ans.push_back(temp);

    for (int i = idx; i < nums.size(); i++) {
        temp.push_back(nums[i]);      // include
        solve(i + 1, nums, temp, ans);
        temp.pop_back();              // backtrack
    }
}

int main() {
    int n;
    cin >> n;

    vector<int> nums(n);

    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        cin >> nums[i];
    }

    vector<vector<int>> ans;
    vector<int> temp;

    solve(0, nums, temp, ans);

    cout << "All possible subsets:\n";

    for (auto subset : ans) {
        cout << "[";

        for (int i = 0; i < subset.size(); i++) {
            cout << subset[i];
            if (i != subset.size() - 1)
                cout << ", ";
        }

        cout << "]\n";
    }

    return 0;
}
